text: Hmmm.... Okay, so I gotta admit, this is the first time I've seen anything of Tarzan that may even be remotely good. Maybe. One concern I had was how the apes looked, the cgi for them doesn't look up to scratch, especially for a movie that's coming out in 2016. My only guess is is that the movie itself has not finished shooting and these bits were the only ones they touched up to release as a teaser, so hopefully there will be a lot more work put into making them look photorealistic, technically the cgi in this movie should look better than the planet of the apes movies. I'm also glad they didn't try to drag Tarzan into the future and have him live in New York or something as I've always hated that about Tarzan movies. I like Margot Robbie, but can't really see her as Jane, she seems miscast in my opinion. Hopefully this could be the Tarzan movie to stand alongside the Disney movie, perhaps even surpass it... Maybe? We'll have to wait and see.

text: To everyone making references about "this better not ruin my childhood": Tarzan was a series of novels (well-written in my opinion) that were very gruesome at times. The story is remarkable but it was never meant to be a story for kids. Disney softened the Tarzan story by A LOT. This looks like it doesn't even want to follow the original story (which I'm ok with, movies are made for different perspectives most of the time). It looks like they just want to make an epic action adventure thing with the story of Tarzan and make it their own. The original story of Tarzan is pretty neat and I'm sorry that it won't be translated in this film. Instead it feels like the jungle meets the avengers, typical Hollywood over-the-top effects with a mediocre story. I'm open minded and I will go see this. Happy holidays to all

text: You can't compare this version to the Disney version because the Disney version was made for kids, and was different from the original story. Despite its dark moments, Disney's Tarzan was still a very upbeat movie. This seems to be going more gritty, more adult-oriented. So it shouldn't be a surprise that the musical aspect is gone. That would be like if Christian Bale played batman in the Dark Knight Rises, but still made jokes like those of Adam West's Batman from the 60s. That being said, I was somewhat confused by the casting choices for some of the roles. But since one of those roles is played by Christoph Waltz, an amazing actor who can fit possibly any role he's given, I get the feeling the casting choices will grow on me once I've seen more screen time from them.

text: All I can say is that this trailer was fantastic, it was visually beautiful, the landscape looked spectacular, definitely the cinematography will be the strongest part of this movie, because I've watched this trailer too many times just admiring the visuals of it, and also the actors, Margot Robbie looks beautiful as Jane Porter, always lovely to watch, Christoph Waltz as the villain, well I'm not sure about that, I'm sure that he is a great actor, but I'm not sure to see him as the villain, and Alexander Skarsgard as the titular character seems fine to me, although I'm pretty sure his fanclub will get more ladies after his portrayal, and Samuel L. Jackson, can't forget about Samuel L. Jackson seeing how he fits inside this cast, so good!     But anyways, this movie is not related to the Disney animated movie, this character has existed for almost 100 years since Edgar Rice Burroughs wrote his first of twelve novels of the character which became popular and even before Disney made the animated movie, it will be based off stories from the original books, but not the Disney movie, as for David Yates as the director, I congratulate him, because seeing the fantastic job he did on Harry Potter makes me want to know more about his director skills, my favorite part was at the end when Tarzan was drinking the coffee, acting natural even though many of the men in the office knew who he was, and the cut!, the final cut of the trailer where Tarzan and the chief Ape get ready to fight, Legendary!!

text: This looks like a TARZAN picture for those of us who came to know Tarzan from the Novels of EDGAR RICE BURROUGHS and not the Sol Lesser films. This film although not based on any of the novels is in keeping with how Tarzan was originally concieved by Burroughs---an English Lord raised by apes known to his peers in the House of Lords as John Clayton lll,Lord Greystoke.  Tarzan had that duality about him-----the feral wild child and the English Lord but no matter how civilized he conducted himself in so-called ""Civilized"" society he knew he didnt belong there. It was for the love of the beautiful blonde American woman JANE PORTER-CLAYTON that he retained his wealth and title of Lordship for her.But Jane knew when to bind him and when to let loose and he HAD to return to the Gabonese rain forest of West Africa revitalize himself. Please read: TARZAN ALIVE; The Biography of Lord Greystoke by PHILIP JOSE FARMER

Revelation 20:14-15 And death and hell were cast into the lake of fire. THIS IS THE SECOND DEATH.  And whosoever was not found written in the book of life was cast into the lake of fire.  DOES ANYONE MEASURE UP TO GOD'S STANDARD?  Romans 3:23 For ALL have sinned, and come short of the glory of God.  HOW CAN WE BE SAVED?  John 3:16 For God so loved the world, that he gave his only begotten Son, that whosoever BELIEVETH in him should not perish, but have everlasting life.  Romans 10:9 That if thou shalt confess with thy mouth the Lord Jesus, and shalt BELIEVE in thine heart that God hath raised him from the dead, thou shalt be saved.  Romans 10:10 For with the heart man BELIEVETH unto righteousness; and with the mouth confession is made unto salvation.  WHAT EXACTLY DID HE DO TO SAVE US?  1 Corinthians 15:3-4 For I delivered unto you first of all that which I also received, how that Christ DIED FOR OUR SINS according to the scriptures; And that he WAS BURIED, and that he ROSE AGAIN THE THIRD DAY according to the scriptures:  1 Peter 3:18 For Christ also hath once SUFFERED FOR SINS, the just for the unjust, that he might bring us to God, being put to death in the flesh, but quickened by the Spirit:  HOW ARE WE CLEANED FROM SIN?  Hebrews 9:22 And almost all things are by the law purged WITH BLOOD; and without shedding of blood is no remission.  Colossians 1:20 And, having made peace through THE BLOOD of his cross, by him to reconcile all things unto himself; by him, I say, whether they be things in earth, or things in heaven.  IS IT FREE OR DO WE HAVE TO DO SOMETHING FOR IT?  Ephesians 2:9 For by grace are ye saved through faith; and that NOT OF YOURSELF: it is the GIFT OF GOD:Not of works, lest any man should boast.  Romans 6:23 For the wages of sin is death; but the GIFT OF GOD is eternal life through Jesus Christ our Lord.  CAN YOU BE CERTAIN THAT YOU ARE SAVED?   I John 5:13 These things have I written unto you that believe on the name of the Son of God; THAT YE MAY KNOW that ye have eternal life, and that ye may BELIEVE on the name of the Son of God.  HOW LONG DOES IT LAST?  John 6:47 Verily, verily, I say unto you, He that believeth on me hath EVERLASTING life.  ARE YOU PROTECTED AGAINST LOSING YOUR SALVATION?  Ephesians 4:30 And grieve not the holy Spirit of God, whereby YE ARE SEALED unto the day of redemption.  Jude 1:1 Jude, the servant of Jesus Christ, and brother of James, to them that are sanctified by God the Father, and PRESERVED in Jesus Christ, and called:  CALL ON HIS NAME!  Psalms 116:13  I will take the cup of salvation, and CALL UPON THE NAME OF LORD.   Romans 10:13  For whosoever shall CALL UPON THE NAME OF THE LORD shall be saved.  Pray: LORD I believe I am a sinner. I know I deserve to go to hell. I believe you are the Son of God, and through your shed blood on the cross I have forgiveness of sins, and by your resurrection I am justified.  Please save me!

text: Before anyone is too harsh about "The Legend of Tarzan", on must remember that these Edgar Rice Burrows stories have been around for many decades and they still endure. I remember as a child watching  film episodes on Saturday morning T.V.  from the 1930's in black and white in Los Angeles. They were immensely entertaining. I find that the way that they have evolved is clever and hope that they continue to do so in the future. I will certainly continue to watch all of the new versions of the stories as I do "James Bond" . Long live Tarzan !

text: Big Tarzan fan here. I read the novel a few times, loved "Greystoke: The Legend of Tarzan" (the definitive Tarzan flick for me) and even dug the Johnny Weissmuller movies as a kid, but man, the new movie... meh.The new "The Legend of Tarzan" (not to be confused with the Greystoke movie) is just not that great. The True Blood guy is great in the roll of Tarzan. He's a good actor anyway. But Samuel L. Jackson in a Tarzan movie... really? Seems he can play ONE character and just doesn't seem to have the acting chops to not be the "Pulp Fiction guy" in every movie. When you have a movie that's taking place in the 1800s, it's kind of stupid for one of the characters to play it like it's the modern day. The movie had potential but his character just was completely unnecessary, unfunny, and distracting. It's like movie studios think "We need to have a guy to say funny things to keep people's attention. We need to give him a 'catch phrase'. Have him say 'Do you want me to kiss this gorilla's nuts?' people will love that!".  The movie's decent but don't believe the hype. It's not all that the marketing would have you believe. It's a rental. The cgi was kind of quirky as well. Too bad, I thought it was going to be way good. By the way, movie studios constantly wring their hands "Darnit, why aren't people going to the movies anymore??" $22 to get in (on a matinee) and $13 for a small soda and small popcorn (?!?!). Imagine taking a family to the movies- It'd be a month's pay. Yikes.

text: It is a good action-adventure movie, that uses a different narrative from the original story, showing us the main character already in the present and using flashbacks to tell us his dramatic past. The lead actor, Alexander Skarsgard, gave us a pretty decent performance, just like his scene partner, Margot Robbie, and the well known Christoph Waltz. It's a decent rereading from an old and classic story, now using all technologies and computer graphics that helps to make a beautiful photography and nice special effects scenes. Although, I missed the Phill Collins remarkable soundtrack. If you are going to watch it, don't try to compare with any previous Tarzan's stories you may have seen or heard.
